# Heat Manager — Development Rules

This file defines how Claude and Cursor should behave when working on this
project. It is based on the official Home Assistant Integration Quality Scale
(Bronze through Platinum) and the specific needs of this project.

Read this file before writing any code.

---

## 1. Project identity and language

All code, comments, docstrings, commit messages, pull request descriptions,
and GitHub issues are written in English without exception.

Danish is only permitted inside the translation file
`custom_components/heat_manager/translations/da.json`. Every new string added
to `en.json` must have a corresponding entry in `da.json` in the same commit.

The integration is built for international use. English is always the
primary language.

---

## 2. Version control — strict semantic versioning

Versions follow the format MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH.

A MAJOR bump means a breaking change to the config entry schema or observable
behaviour. A MINOR bump means a new feature, new entity, or new service that
is backwards compatible. A PATCH bump means a bug fix, translation update, or
documentation change only.

The version is declared in exactly one place: the `"version"` key in
`manifest.json`. All other references must match it and must be updated in the
same commit.

Never commit a version bump without a matching entry in `CHANGELOG.md`.
Never skip a version number.

---

## 3. Git commit conventions

Every commit message follows this format:

    type(scope): short description of what you did

The first line must be 72 characters or fewer. A body with more detail can
follow after a blank line.

**Allowed types:**
- `feat` — new feature, entity, or service
- `fix` — bug fix (reference the bug ID if one exists, e.g. "fix(window): B3 - ...")
- `docs` — README, CHANGELOG, or docstrings only, no logic changed
- `test` — adding or updating tests only
- `refactor` — code cleaned up with no behaviour change
- `chore` — version bump, manifest update, CI configuration
- `trans` — translation strings only in en.json or da.json
- `style` — formatting only after running ruff, no logic change

**Allowed scopes** — use the name of the module or feature:
`controller`, `presence`, `window`, `preheat`, `season`, `waste`,
`coordinator`, `config_flow`, `entities`, `frontend`, `tests`, `docs`, `ci`

**Real examples from this project:**

    feat(controller): add ON/PAUSE/OFF state machine with guard decorator
    fix(window): B3 - restore schedule only when presence is active on close
    fix(window): B1 - remove leading dot from lukas_vindue_contact entity ID
    docs(readme): add HACS installation instructions and service examples
    chore(manifest): bump version 0.1.0 → 0.1.1
    test(controller): add regression test for auto-off via season trigger
    trans(da): add Danish strings for controller_state and season_mode

Always use the imperative form: "add", "fix", "remove" — never "added" or
"fixes". No period at the end of the subject line. One logical change per
commit. If the commit closes a GitHub issue, add "Closes #12" on a line in
the body.

---

## 4. Branching strategy

`main` is always release-ready. Only merge here when releasing a tagged version.
`dev` is the integration branch. All features and fixes merge here first.
Feature branches are named `feature/<description>` and branch off `dev`.
Bug fix branches are named `fix/<description>` and branch off `dev`.
Documentation branches are named `docs/<description>` and branch off `dev`.

Examples: `feature/preheat-engine`, `fix/b1-lukas-window-typo`,
`docs/readme-hacs-install`

---

## 5. File and code structure

All integration files live under `custom_components/heat_manager/`.

All logic that does not depend on `homeassistant.*` lives in `engine/`. Engine
files must be importable and unit-testable without a running Home Assistant
instance. This is the most important architectural rule in the project.

Platform files — `sensor.py`, `binary_sensor.py`, `select.py`, `switch.py` —
contain only entity class definitions and `async_setup_entry`. No logic.

`coordinator.py` is the single source of truth for shared state. It owns the
`DataUpdateCoordinator` and instantiates all engines.

`const.py` is the single source of truth for all constants. No magic strings
anywhere else in the codebase. If you find yourself writing a string literal
that looks like an entity ID, a service name, or a state value, it belongs in
`const.py`.

The dependency direction flows one way: platforms → coordinator → engines →
const. Circular imports are never acceptable.

---

## 6. Home Assistant Quality Scale — Bronze (required before any release)

These rules come directly from the official HA IQS Bronze tier and must all
be satisfied before the 0.1.0 release.

The integration must be set up exclusively through the UI config flow with no
YAML setup supported. `config_flow.py` must implement `async_step_user`.

The config flow test file must cover all steps and all error paths. Run with
`pytest tests/ --cov=custom_components/heat_manager`.

`async_step_user` must call `self._async_abort_if_unique_id_configured()` after
setting a stable unique ID. Only one Heat Manager instance is allowed per HA
installation.

Every entity must have a `unique_id` using the format
`f"{entry.entry_id}_{entity_suffix}"`, for example `"abc123_kitchen_state"`.

Every entity class must set `has_entity_name = True`. Entity display names come
from `strings.json` translations, never from hardcoded Python strings.

The coordinator is stored in `entry.runtime_data`, not in `hass.data[DOMAIN]`.
The access pattern everywhere is `coordinator = entry.runtime_data`.

All services are registered in `async_setup_entry` inside `__init__.py`, not
in `async_setup`.

The config flow must validate that all provided entity IDs exist in the HA
state machine before creating the entry. It returns an `errors` dict on failure.

`async_setup_entry` must raise `ConfigEntryNotReady` if the coordinator's first
refresh fails, for example if climate entities are unavailable at startup.

State change listeners are registered in `async_added_to_hass()` and removed
in `async_will_remove_from_hass()`, never in `__init__`.

The polling interval is `timedelta(seconds=60)` set in `coordinator.py`. This
is appropriate because the integration only polls local HA entity states with
no external API calls.

Since there are no external library dependencies, `requirements` is an empty
list in `manifest.json`. All HA built-ins are used via `homeassistant.*` imports.

The `brands/` directory must contain `icon.png` (256×256) and `icon@2x.png`
(512×512) for HACS display.

`README.md` must include a high-level description, step-by-step installation
for both HACS and manual install, all configuration options with types and
defaults, all service actions with parameters, and removal instructions.

---

## 7. Home Assistant Quality Scale — Silver (current target)

Service handlers must raise `ServiceValidationError` with a translatable
message key on failure. Never swallow errors silently or raise generic
`Exception`.

`async_unload_entry` must unload all platforms and cancel all listeners. The
integration must be loadable, unloadable, and reloadable without side effects.

If a configured climate entity reports state `"unavailable"`, the corresponding
Heat Manager sensor must be marked unavailable too. Never serve stale data.

`codeowners` in `manifest.json` must always reflect the current active
maintainer. Currently `["@kingpainter"]`.

When a climate entity becomes unavailable, log once at `WARNING` level. When
it recovers, log once at `INFO` level. Repeated log spam is not acceptable.

Set `PARALLEL_UPDATES = 1` in each platform file. All updates flow through
the coordinator — no direct parallel polling from individual entities.

Target test coverage is above 95% line coverage across all `engine/` and
platform files. Measure with `pytest --cov=custom_components/heat_manager
--cov-report=term-missing`.

The reauthentication flow rule is exempt because this integration has no
authentication. This is documented in `quality_scale.yaml`.

---

## 8. Home Assistant Quality Scale — Gold (aspirational)

All entity names are defined in `strings.json` and `translations/*.json`.
No hardcoded display names in Python.

Use HA device classes wherever one applies. `sensor.energy_wasted_today` uses
`SensorDeviceClass.ENERGY`. `binary_sensor.any_window_open` uses
`BinarySensorDeviceClass.WINDOW`. `binary_sensor.heating_wasted` uses
`BinarySensorDeviceClass.HEAT`.

Diagnostic sensors such as `pause_remaining` and `efficiency_score` use
`EntityCategory.DIAGNOSTIC`. Config switches such as room overrides use
`EntityCategory.CONFIG`.

`diagnostics.py` must implement `async_get_config_entry_diagnostics()` returning
a sanitised snapshot of all room states, controller state, season mode, and
config with no personally identifiable information.

The options flow allows editing global settings and notification preferences
after initial setup. This is already implemented via `HeatManagerOptionsFlow`.

If a configured climate entity is not found at startup, raise a `RepairIssue`
with a link to reconfigure rather than silently failing.

The README must include at least three real-world automation examples using
Heat Manager services, a troubleshooting section covering the four most common
failure scenarios, and a section on known limitations.

---

## 9. Code quality standards

Use `ruff format` for formatting, not black. Run it before every commit.
Use `ruff check` with HA's ruleset. Zero warnings are allowed at commit time.

All function signatures must be fully typed including explicit `-> None` return
types. Use `from __future__ import annotations` at the top of every Python file.

Never use bare `except:`. Always catch specific exception types. Never use
mutable default arguments in function signatures.

Every module that logs must have `_LOGGER = logging.getLogger(__name__)` at
the top. Use f-strings for all string formatting, never `%` formatting or
`.format()`. Maximum line length is 88 characters.

All async functions that call `hass.services.async_call` must pass
`blocking=True` unless there is a documented reason in a comment explaining
why not.

---

## 10. Testing rules

Every engine file has a corresponding test file following this naming pattern:
`engine/controller.py` → `tests/.../test_controller_engine.py`.

Every bug fix gets a regression test named after the bug ID:
`test_bug_b1_lukas_window_never_shown()`, `test_bug_b3_window_close_ignores_presence()`.

Every new service gets at least one happy-path test and one error-path test.

All tests use `pytest-asyncio`. All async tests are decorated with
`@pytest.mark.asyncio`. Tests use `MagicMock` and `AsyncMock` for HA
dependencies. Never import real HA core in engine tests. Tests must run
completely offline with no HA instance required.

Test observable behaviour, not implementation details.

---

## 11. Changelog rules

`CHANGELOG.md` follows the Keep a Changelog format from keepachangelog.com.
Each version section contains only the headings that apply to that release:
Added, Changed, Fixed, Removed, Security. Empty headings are omitted.

The `[Unreleased]` section always exists at the top and is where new entries
are written as work is done. On release, rename it to `[X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD`
and create a fresh empty `[Unreleased]` section above it.

Every bug fix entry references its bug ID: "Fixed B1 — lukas_vindue typo in
Vis åbne vinduer automation". Every entry is a complete sentence ending with
a period. Version numbers are linked to GitHub compare or release URLs.

---

## 12. README rules

The README must always contain these sections in this order: title and one-line
description, status badges (version, HA min version, HACS, license), what it
does in plain language, features list, requirements, installation via HACS and
manual, configuration with all options and defaults, services reference, entities
reference, Lovelace card usage, at least three automation examples, troubleshooting,
known limitations, changelog link, and license.

The README is always in English. A `README_da.md` may exist as a companion but
is never the primary file and is not linked from HACS.

---

## 13. quality_scale.yaml

`quality_scale.yaml` inside `custom_components/heat_manager/` tracks the
implementation status of every IQS rule. Valid statuses are `done`, `todo`,
and `exempt`. Every rule must have an entry. Rules marked `exempt` must have
a `comment` field explaining why the rule does not apply. This file is updated
in the same commit as the code that satisfies the rule.

---

## 14. What Claude must never do

Never store the coordinator in `hass.data[DOMAIN]`. Always use `runtime_data`.

Never hardcode entity IDs inside engine files. Entity IDs come from the config
entry data passed through the coordinator.

Never write Danish in Python files, commit messages, or GitHub issue titles.

Never bump the version in `manifest.json` without updating `CHANGELOG.md` in
the same commit.

Never add a new constant directly in a platform file. It belongs in `const.py`.

Never write business logic in a platform file. Logic belongs in `engine/`.

Never use `time.sleep()` or any blocking I/O. Everything must be async.

Never catch `Exception` broadly without a specific reason documented in a
comment with a `noqa` tag.

Never commit with failing tests.

Never merge to `main` without a version bump and a `CHANGELOG.md` entry.

Never write a test that requires a live Home Assistant instance to run.

Never add a TODO comment without a GitHub issue number in the format
`# TODO(#42): description of what needs doing`.
